SIMPLE: shade
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shade
<hw>Shade</hw> <pr>(sh⟦amac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>shade</ets>, <ets>shadewe</ets>, <ets>schadewe</ets>, AS.
<ets>sceadu</ets>, <ets>scead</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>skado</ets>, D.
<ets>schaduw</ets>, OHG. <ets>scato</ets>, (gen. <ets>scatewes</ets>),
G. <ets>schatten</ets>, Goth. <ets>skadus</ets>, Ir. & Gael.
<ets>sgath</ets>, and probably to Gr. <grk>sko`tos</grk> darkness.
⟦root⟧162. Cf. <er>Shadow</er>, <er>Shed</er> a hat.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Comparative obscurity owing to interception or interruption of the
rays of light; partial darkness caused by the intervention of something
between the space contemplated and the source of light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Shade</xex> differs from <xex>shadow</xex> as it
implies no particular form or definite limit; whereas a
<xex>shadow</xex> represents in form the object which intercepts the
light. When we speak of the <xex>shade</xex> of a tree, we have no
reference to its form; but when we speak of measuring a pyramid or other
object by its <xex>shadow</xex>, we have reference to its form and
extent.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Darkness; obscurity; -- often in the
plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>shades</qex> of night were falling fast.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An obscure place; a spot not exposed to light;
hence, a secluded retreat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us seek out some desolate <qex>shade</qex>, and there⟦br⟧
Weep our sad bosoms empty.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which intercepts, or shelters from, light or
the direct rays of the sun; hence, also, that which protects from heat
or currents of air; a screen; protection; shelter; cover; <as>as, a lamp
<ex>shade</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord is thy <qex>shade</qex> upon thy right hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. cxxi. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sleep under a fresh tree's <qex>shade</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let the arched knife well sharpened now assail the spreading
<qex>shades</qex> of vegetables.</q> <rj><qau>J. Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Shadow.</def> <mark>[Poetic.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Envy will merit, as its <qex>shade</qex>, pursue.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The soul after its separation from the body; -- so
called because the ancients it to be perceptible to the sight, though
not to the touch; a spirit; a ghost; <as>as, the <ex>shades</ex> of
departed heroes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Swift as thought the flitting <qex>shade</qex>⟦br⟧
Thro' air his momentary journey made.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Painting, Drawing, etc.)</fld> <def>The darker
portion of a picture; a less illuminated part. See Def. 1,
above.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Degree or variation of color, as darker or lighter,
stronger or paler; <as>as, a delicate <ex>shade</ex> of
pink</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>White, red, yellow, blue, with their several degrees, or
<qex>shades</qex> and mixtures, as green only in by the eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A minute difference or variation, as of thought,
belief, expression, etc.; also, the quality or degree of anything which
is distinguished from others similar by slight differences; <as>as, the
<ex>shades</ex> of meaning in synonyms</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>New <qex>shades</qex> and combinations of thought.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every <qex>shade</qex> of religious and political opinion has its
own headquarters.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Shades</b></col>, <cd>the Nether World; the supposed
abode of souls after leaving the body.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shade
<hw>Shade</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Shaded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shelter or screen
by intercepting the rays of light; to keep off illumination from.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I went to crop the sylvan scenes,⟦br⟧
And <qex>shade</qex> our altars with their leafy greens.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shelter; to cover from injury; to protect; to
screen; to hide; <as>as, to <ex>shade</ex> one's eyes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ere in our own house I do <qex>shade</qex> my head.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To obscure; to dim the brightness of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou <qex>shad'st</qex>⟦br⟧
The full blaze of thy beams.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To pain in obscure colors; to darken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To mark with gradations of light or color.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To present a shadow or image of; to shadow forth; to
represent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The goddess] in her person cunningly did <qex>shade</qex>⟦br⟧
That part of Justice which is Equity.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shade
<hw>Shade</hw> <pr>(sh⟦amac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Shade</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To undergo or exhibit minute
difference or variation, as of color, meaning, expression, etc.; to pass
by slight changes; -- used chiefly with a preposition, as
<xex>into</xex>, <xex>away</xex>, <xex>off</xex>.</def></p>

<p><q>This small group will be most conveniently treated with the
emotional division, into which it <qex>shades</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Edmund
Gurney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shadeful</ent>⟦br⟧
